[AI]
Of course! Building a simple calculator is a great project to start with.

I propose we build a desktop application using Python and its built-in Tkinter library. This is a fantastic choice because it doesn't require any external dependencies and is perfect for creating simple graphical user interfaces (GUIs).

Here's my vision for the project structure:

1.  **`main.py`**: The main entry point of our application. It will be responsible for creating the application window and starting the calculator.
2.  **`calculator_ui.py`**: This file will define the `CalculatorUI` class, which will handle creating and arranging all the visual elements like the display screen and the buttons.
3.  **`calculator_logic.py`**: This file will contain the `CalculatorLogic` class, which will manage the calculator's state and handle all the mathematical operations.

This separation of concerns (UI vs. Logic) is a best practice that will make our code cleaner, more organized, and easier to expand upon later.

First, I'll lay down the foundational code for these three files, creating a visual but non-functional calculator. After you approve this initial structure, we can move on to wiring up the logic to make the buttons work.

I'll also remove the `TestFile.py` as it's not needed for this project.

